<subSubSection id="C33E71FB04593F138BD38E239C333D94" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="196" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9B227004593F138BD38E239C333D94" blockId="4.[151,1437,1245,2027]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,153,432]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="196" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204593F128BD38E23980C3B5B" bold="true" box="[199,315,1893,1919]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Remarks.</emphasis>
The association of the male of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304593F1289878E239BD43B5B" authorityName="Waichert &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2013" box="[659,739,1893,1919]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="giga">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204593F1289878E239BD43B5B" box="[659,739,1893,1919]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">A. giga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the female is based on similarities in wing venation, wing coloration and distribution. The male specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304593F1289C58ECF9A153B87" authorityName="Waichert &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2013" box="[721,802,1929,1955]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="giga">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204593F1289C58ECF9A153B87" box="[721,802,1929,1955]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">A. giga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="131F3EF504593F1288258ECF9AA13B87" box="[817,918,1929,1955]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1138,1163]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,182,1112]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,181,1112]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–11. Male of Abernessia giga. 7) Dorsal view, 8) Head, 9) Lateral view, 10) Genitalia, ventral view, 11) Genitalia, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3898092" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3898092/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Figs 7–9</figureCitation>
) looks similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304593F128F488ECF9D883B87" box="[1116,1215,1929,1955]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prima">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204593F128F488ECF9D883B87" box="[1116,1215,1929,1955]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">A. prima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304593F128FE28ECF9C4A3B87" authorityName="Waichert &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2013" box="[1270,1405,1929,1955]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204593F128FE28ECF9C4A3B87" box="[1270,1405,1929,1955]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">A. capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304593F128AD38EEB9B783BE3" authorityName="Waichert &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2013" box="[455,591,1965,1991]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204593F128AD38EEB9B783BE3" box="[455,591,1965,1991]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">A. capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having pale markings on the wings, white markings on the metasoma, and the SGP distinctly narrowed midway with apex truncated. It can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304593F128F858E979DC43BCF" box="[1169,1267,2001,2027]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prima">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204593F128F858E979DC43BCF" box="[1169,1267,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">A. prima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by also having pale markings on the wings and the SGP distinctly narrowed midway with apex truncated, in addition to the clypeus being completely black and having more prominent hind tibial teeth with smaller distance between each tooth. 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304583F138B8389A7987A3CDF" authorityName="Waichert &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2013" box="[151,333,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="giga">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204583F138B8389A7987A3CDF" box="[151,333,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="196">Abernessia giga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304583F13890189A79BAC3CDF" box="[533,667,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capibaxa">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204583F13890189A79BAC3CDF" box="[533,667,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="196">A. capibaxa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the SMC3 short, as long as wide, square-shaped; whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304583F138BA2884398083D3B" authorityName="Waichert &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2013" box="[182,319,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204583F138BA2884398083D3B" box="[182,319,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="196">A. capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the SMC3 cell is about 2× as long as wide, rectangular-shaped. The male specimen matches the wing coloration of the previously recorded female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304583F1389E3886F9A7E3D67" authorityName="Waichert &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2013" box="[759,841,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="giga">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204583F1389E3886F9A7E3D67" box="[759,841,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="196">A. giga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and was collected in the same ecoregion. Molecular sequencing may prove that these male characters correspond to intraspecific variation, as the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304583F138FBD880B9DCD3D43" authorityName="Waichert &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2013" box="[1193,1274,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="giga">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204583F138FBD880B9DCD3D43" box="[1193,1274,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="196">A. giga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimen was collected close to the locations of three of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304583F13898488379BC73DAF" box="[656,752,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prima">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204583F13898488379BC73DAF" box="[656,752,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="196">A. prima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males listed above (
<figureCitation id="131F3EF504583F1388C588379D263DAF" box="[977,1041,369,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1490,1515]" captionTargetBox="[163,1380,534,1459]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[372,1351,975,1015]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution of species of Abernessia within South American Ecoregions. Red shapes represent previous distribution records, while green shapes represent newly reported records of occurrence. Triangle represents A. capixaba, star represents A. irmagardae, circle represents A. giga, and square represents A. prima." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3898088" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3898088/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="196">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Additionally, the metasoma white patches greatly vary in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304583F138A8888D398C83D8B" box="[412,511,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prima">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204583F138A8888D398C83D8B" box="[412,511,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="196">A. prima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and one 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304583F13897F88D39BC43D8B" box="[619,755,405,431]" pageId="5" pageNumber="196" rank="variety" variety="does">variety does</taxonomicName>
match that of the described 
<taxonomicName id="4C2459F304583F138F2588D39DB53D8B" authorityName="Waichert &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2013" box="[1073,1154,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Abernessia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="giga">
<emphasis id="B950FE6204583F138F2588D39DB53D8B" box="[1073,1154,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="196">A. giga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="131F3EF504583F138F8488D39DC03D94" box="[1168,1271,405,432]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,181,1912]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[164,1424,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2–6. Dorsal images of metasoma showing white spot pattern variations of male Abernessia prima in comparison to the single male specimen of A. giga, 2) A. prima EMUS_817, 3) A. prima EMUS_818, 4) A. prima EMUS_819, 5) A. prima EMUS_820, 6) A. giga EMUS_816." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3898090" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3898090/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="196">Figs 4–6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
